<br>
I looked at my logs to see why this was happening.  I noticed the following:<br>
<br>
  1.  The first hit was nearly always at max.  <br>
  2.  The first five hits averaged larger that the next five hits.<br>
<br>
Since I was now switching from the stein to my weapon, I thought that might explain 1. and 2.  So I switched back to my weapon in my hand.  After this switch, I was doing much better, but still was taking more damage than before.  I looked at the logs again and noticed that while 1. was still true, 2 was no longer true.  I then turned my attack on at the start of every combat and sure enough that first hit dropped to an average hit.  <br>
<br>
From this I decided the following:<br>
<br>
  1. Having you attack on when hit mitigates damage.<br>
  2. Having a much higher attack value mitigates damage.<br>
<br>
Having decided this, I went to the bazaar and bought a picering weapon with a high INT on it.  This weapon, just happend to have a much lower delay than my previous weapon. <br>
<br>
Later, I was using the back pet off  the giant while it was running and stike it from behind to get skillups.  I was amazed at how much the lower delay helped get more strikes which led to more skillups.  <br>
<br>
For mages to maintain their max combat offense skills, the lower delay is really important.  Mages get 5 skillups per level, but are not nearly as effective as the cleric's 4  skillups be level.  Must be on a different combat chart.  <br>
<br>
To this day, when I am in a combat situation, I have my best skilled weapon in my primary hand and attack turned on, even though I very seldom get into combat.  <br>
<br>
